        <body>

            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; Friday&#44; Parasha Behar &#40;May&#41;<lb/> <date>1854</date>.</p>
            <p>To my beloved friend etc <addressee>Yitzchok Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44;</p>
            <p>Sir and Dear Friend&#44;</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your delightful letter reached me and<lb/> from the depths of my heart I express my
                thanks<lb/> for your affection. It is true I have wherewith<lb/> to support my
                family and I thank God for this<lb/> kindness but the real reason that I wrote
                to<lb/> you is that I saw in your book&#42; that over<lb/> there they are willing to
                pay &#36;3500 as a per&#8211;<lb/>manent salary. The canto urged me to write to<lb/>
                them but before writing I thought I ought to<lb/> write to you. For if I remain here
                all the days of my<lb/> life&#44; I could not support my family in my old<lb/>
                age&#44; and what will I eat on the 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> year&#42;&#63; That<lb/>
                is the reason why it occurred to me to leave here.<lb/> Since you my friend have
                decided in your great wis&#8211;<lb/>dom that this ought not to be done&#44; I shall
                re&#8211;<lb/>frain&#44; and the good God will support me in<lb/> my old age just as in his
                great kindness<lb/> he supports all the creatures who look to his aid.<lb/> Your
                eternal friend&#44;<lb/> <persName role="author">Simon Cohen Noot</persName><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>&#42;probably the Occident &#42;a reference to the year of<lb/> Shemitah&#44; when no work could
                be done<lb/> and one laid on one&#39;s savings</p>

        </body>
